      undisturbed; but while her eyes were still upon the Countess, she drew her
      head gently back, imperceptibly. If anything, she was admiring the lady;
      but Rose could be no placid philosophic spectator of what was to her a
      horrible assumption and hypocrisy. For the sake of him she loved, she had
      swallowed a nauseous cup bravely. The Countess was too much for her. She
      felt sick to think of being allied to this person. She had a shuddering
      desire to run into the ranks of the world, and hide her head from
      multitudinous hootings. With a pang of envy she saw her friend Jenny
